</ul></div></nav><div class="site-inner"><div class="content-sidebar-wrap"><main class="content" role="main" itemprop="mainContentOfPage" itemscope="itemscope" itemtype="http://schema.org/Blog"><article class="post-1276 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail category-dessert category-drinks category-vegetarian entry" itemscope="itemscope" itemtype="http://schema.org/BlogPosting" itemprop="blogPost"><header class="entry-header"><h1 class="entry-title" itemprop="headline">Mexican Chocolate Atole</h1> 
<p class="entry-meta"><time class="entry-time" itemprop="datePublished" datetime="2015-10-26T19:23:34+00:00">October 26, 2015</time> by <span class="entry-author" itemprop="author" itemscope="itemscope" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><a href="http://sweetlittlekitchen.com/author/alexa/" class="entry-author-link" itemprop="url" rel="author"><span class="entry-author-name" itemprop="name">Alexa</span></a></span> <span class="entry-comments-link"><a href="http://sweetlittlekitchen.com/mexican-chocolate-atole/#comments">2 Comments</a></span> </p></header><div class="entry-content" itemprop="text"><p>I am embracing fall foods like pumpkin rooibos tea from Trader Joe&#8217;s, stuffed acorn squash, and the delicious chili cookoff at work today. And there&#8217;s one unique cold weather drink I want to introduce you to. Meet Atole.</p>
<p><a href="http://sweetlittlekitchen.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/atole-21.jpg">
		<span class="pibfi_pinterest ">
		<img class="alignnone wp-image-1284 size-full" src="http://sweetlittlekitchen.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/atole-21.jpg" alt="Mexican Chocolate Atole is a hot drink made from ground corn that's surprisingly simple and just waiting to be a part of your cold weather drink line-up. Think chocolate cereal milk in hot chocolate form." width="550" height="825">
			<span class="xc_pin" onclick="pin_this(event, 'http://pinterest.com/pin/create/button/?url=http://sweetlittlekitchen.com/mexican-chocolate-atole/&amp;media=http://sweetlittlekitchen.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/atole-21.jpg&amp;description=Mexican Chocolate Atole')">
			</span>
		</span>
	</a></p>
<p>Atole is a Mexican hot drink made from ground field corn mixed with water to form a thick beverage. It is highly customizable and comes in a slew of different flavors &#8211; chocolate, peanut, blueberry, and chili to name a few.</p>
<p>I know many of you might be wondering why you should ever make this weird corn drink when you can just mix up a pack of Swiss Miss. But it&#8217;s so delicious. It&#8217;s creamy and thick with little dairy, sweet and chocolately with a corn undertone reminiscent of the leftover milk from a bowl of cocoa puffs. And it&#8217;s inexpensive and free from nasty preservatives. I rest my case.</p>
<p>Pictured below is the brand of masa harina para tortillas I used. I found it at my local Kroger in the flour section and it was less than $2.50 for the giant bag. If you&#8217;re really having a hard time finding it, there&#8217;s always <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Maseca-Instant-Yellow-Corn-Flour/dp/B004TD5FJK/ref=sr_1_sc_2?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1445905057&amp;sr=8-2-spell&amp;keywords=masceca">Amazon</a>.</p>
<p><a href="http://sweetlittlekitchen.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/atole-3.jpg">
		<span class="pibfi_pinterest ">
		<img class="alignnone wp-image-1279 size-full" src="http://sweetlittlekitchen.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/atole-3.jpg" alt="Mexican Chocolate Atole is a hot drink made from ground corn that's surprisingly simple and just waiting to be a part of your cold weather drink line-up. Think chocolate cereal milk in hot chocolate form." width="550" height="825">
			<span class="xc_pin" onclick="pin_this(event, 'http://pinterest.com/pin/create/button/?url=http://sweetlittlekitchen.com/mexican-chocolate-atole/&amp;media=http://sweetlittlekitchen.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/atole-3.jpg&amp;description=Mexican Chocolate Atole')">
			</span>
		</span>
	</a></p>
<p>Again, Atole is highly customizable. You can always some brown sugar to the recipe to make it sweeter or more water to make it thinner. You wouldn&#8217;t be remiss to add a dash of cayenne pepper, making it truly a Mexican Chocolate. The world is your oyster.</p>
<p><a href="http://sweetlittlekitchen.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/atole-1.jpg">
		<span class="pibfi_pinterest ">
		<img class="alignnone wp-image-1280 size-full" src="http://sweetlittlekitchen.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/atole-1.jpg" alt="Mexican Chocolate Atole is a hot drink made from ground corn that's surprisingly simple and just waiting to be a part of your cold weather drink line-up. Think chocolate cereal milk in hot chocolate form." width="550" height="825">
			<span class="xc_pin" onclick="pin_this(event, 'http://pinterest.com/pin/create/button/?url=http://sweetlittlekitchen.com/mexican-chocolate-atole/&amp;media=http://sweetlittlekitchen.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/atole-1.jpg&amp;description=Mexican Chocolate Atole')">
			</span>
		</span>
	</a></p>
<p>And, um, I had to put a picture of Nala in, with her still being a new addition and all. I&#8217;m terrible about remembering to take pictures of her when she&#8217;s actually doing cute things. But she sure does love to sleep on those Dominion boxes. And I&#8217;m enough of a sucker to keep them out and let her do it, even though she&#8217;s knocked them over 3 times already and I&#8217;ve had to reorganize hundreds of cards.</p>
<p><a href="http://sweetlittlekitchen.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/nala-cat-atole.jpg">
		<span class="pibfi_pinterest ">
		<img class="alignnone wp-image-1278 size-full" src="http://sweetlittlekitchen.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/nala-cat-atole.jpg" alt="Mexican Chocolate Atole is a hot drink made from ground corn that's surprisingly simple and just waiting to be a part of your cold weather drink line-up. Think chocolate cereal milk in hot chocolate form. " width="550" height="825">
			<span class="xc_pin" onclick="pin_this(event, 'http://pinterest.com/pin/create/button/?url=http://sweetlittlekitchen.com/mexican-chocolate-atole/&amp;media=http://sweetlittlekitchen.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/nala-cat-atole.jpg&amp;description=Mexican Chocolate Atole')">
			</span>
		</span>
	</a></p>
<p>Stay warm and enjoy a steaming hot mug of atole!<br />
<div id="easyrecipe-1276-0" class="easyrecipe" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Recipe"> <div itemprop="name" class="ERSName">Mexican Chocolate Atole</div> <div class="ERSClear">&nbsp;</div> <div class="ERSTopRight"> <img itemprop="image" src="http://sweetlittlekitchen.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/banner-atole-300x174.jpg" width="205"/> <div class="ERSSavePrint"> <span class="ERSSaveBtnSpan"><a href="" class="ERSSaveBtn bigoven">Save</a></span> <span class="ERSPrintBtnSpan"><a class="ERSPrintBtn" href="http://sweetlittlekitchen.com/easyrecipe-print/1276-0/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Print</a></span> </div> </div> <div class="ERSTimes"> <div class="ERSTime ERSTimeRight"> <div class="ERSTimeHeading">Cook time</div> <div class="ERSTimeItem"> <time itemprop="cookTime" datetime="PT15M">15 mins</time> </div> </div> <div class="ERSTime ERSTimeRight"> <div class="ERSTimeHeading">Total time</div> <div class="ERSTimeItem"> <time itemprop="totalTime" datetime="PT15M">15 mins</time> </div> </div> <div class="ERSClearLeft">&nbsp;</div> </div> <div itemprop="description" class="ERSSummary">Mexican Chocolate Atole is a hot drink made from ground corn that's surprisingly simple and just waiting to be a part of your cold weather drink line-up. Think chocolate cereal milk in hot chocolate form.</div> <div class="divERSHeadItems"> <div class="ERSServes">Serves: <span itemprop="recipeYield">4 servings</span></div> </div> <div class="ERSIngredients"> <div class="ERSIngredientsHeader ERSHeading">Ingredients</div> <ul> <li class="ingredient" itemprop="ingredients">• &frac12; cup masa harina para tortillas</li> <li class="ingredient" itemprop="ingredients">• 3 cups water, plus more as needed</li> <li class="ingredient" itemprop="ingredients">• 1 cup milk</li> <li class="ingredient" itemprop="ingredients">• 3&frac12; ounces milk chocolate, broken into pieces</li> <li class="ingredient" itemprop="ingredients">• &frac12; teaspoon ground cinnamon</li> <li class="ingredient" itemprop="ingredients">• pinch of salt</li> </ul> <div class="ERSClear"></div> </div> <div class="ERSInstructions"> <div class="ERSInstructionsHeader ERSHeading">Instructions</div> <ol> <li class="instruction" itemprop="recipeInstructions">In a large saucepan, add masa over medium heat. Immediately add the water in a slow stream, constantly whisking to avoid clumps. Bring to a simmer and whisk in milk, chocolate, cinnamon, and a pinch of salt until chocolate has melted, about one minute.</li> <li class="instruction" itemprop="recipeInstructions">Lower the heat and return to a simmer. Continue whisking constantly for 5 minutes. Thin with additional water if needed. Froth with a whisk and ladle into mugs. Serve immediately.</li> </ol> <div class="ERSClear"></div> </div> <div class="endeasyrecipe" title="style002" style="display: none">3.4.3177</div> </div><br />
Adapted from <a href="http://www.seriouseats.com/recipes/2015/02/champurrado-mexican-hot-chocolate-corn-drink-recipe.html">Serious Eats</a></p>
